	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Having hit level 21 last night, I decided to look back on the things I did right and wrong in the past few months with my monk character.  Certainly, I wouldn't want to change classes for a second!  Though I miss the arcane adventuring (not to mention raw power) of being a spellcaster, as well as the cool equipment of the warrior, experience has taught me that monks can be the most powerful class in the game.  <BR>
<BR>
Why?  Several reasons, and tips, which I hope will help some of you aspiring young monks.<BR>
<BR>
1) Monks are the least dependant on money, but have plenty of uses for it if they wish.  What this means is that you could do very well with virtually no armor; monks have naturally high AC and ATK values that are not dependant on equipment(very convenient when you have to run to retrive your corpse and get jumped by a roving mob).  I've heard people say that monks can only wear leather... well, that's not true by a long shot.  There are plenty of very exciting  (and very expensive) rare forms of armor that monks can wear with ease.  Though you won't need more than 40pp for a set of mesh armor (it's common in Upper Guk and very few classes are as excited to wear it as monks are), move on from there and you'll find that you'll need lots of money very quickly to buy the rareist of the rare.  But the beautiful part is, you don't ever NEED to go this route at all!  You could lead a very happy and healthy life as a monk with nothing but basic cloth on your back.<BR>
<BR>
If you choose to go the high style life, I'd recommend the following armor for their quality and low weight:<BR>
<BR>
Lockjaw Hide Vest/Tunic (12 AC 5 STA) <BR>
- This can be found in the Oasis of Marr off of Lockjaw, a nasty level 23ish crocodile that spawns periodically.  At this point in the game he is killed fairly quickly by high level folks because he sometimes carries a high level staff.  You can pick one of these up for around 20pp.  They usually sell quick though so you might find yourself in a bidding war ;)<BR>
<BR>
Mesh Armor (Variable AC from 2 to 8 per piece)<BR>
- This armor, which protects more or less like leather and looks like leather when worn is a very solid choice for monks because of its low weight.  It's found in Upper Guk off of &quot;Gaz&quot; and harder frogloks, and can be bought for generally very little money (about 1-2pp per AC) since it has a one-class audience.<BR>
<BR>
Woven and Netted Armor (Between 1 and 6 AC)<BR>
- Not the best choice, but better than cloth, these types of armor are generally lightweight.  Being cloth based, they won't win you any points for not looking like a newbie, but do the job.  Woven is usually overpriced since casters look for it, so if given the choice go for mesh.  All mesh, woven and netted armor is magical in nature and will allow you to hit magic-only creatures (wisps, elementals, dry &amp; ice boned skeletons etc) if you get ahold of gloves.<BR>
<BR>
Azure Sleeves (12 AC)<BR>
- By the time you need this kind of armor you had better be one rich monk, because these things sell for a fortune.  A very rare spawn in Lower Guk (a level 30+ dungeon), everyone wants these things because of their high AC.  Of interest to monks, they are also very lightweight.  At this level you will probably have to trade for these... so hang on to some of the nicer things you get to barter with later.<BR>
<BR>
Thick Leather Apron (8 AC)<BR>
- Worn in your belt slot, this item provides very nice AC for only 1 pound of weight.  They are found in Unrest, but are sold all over by players for between 12-24pp.<BR>
<BR>
Flowing Black Silk Sash<BR>
- Another very nice item that will cost you an arm and a leg, this belt slot item will speed up your attacks as if you have the spell Haste cast on you at all times.  Good luck finding this one, because EVERYONE wants it.<BR>
<BR>
I would also recommend some of the magical bracers out there, such as silver-plated bracers (Upper Guk), symbol of loyalty to vox (Permafrost), etc., and a good weight reducing container such as the travelers backpack (Najena) or Pierce's Pounch of Storing (Rivervale).  The latter will allow you to carry lots more loot without exceeding your 14 pound weight limit.  Jewelry is also important, and can provide some nice bonuses for virtually no weight.  Focus on things like agility and magic resistance: nothing slows down a monk like the root spell.<BR>
<BR>
2) Feign death.  I cannot stress how great of a skill this is - only necromancers and monks have it, and it has virtually eliminated death from my character's daily routine.  There is no other skill, aside from perhaps a trade skill, worth pumping your pratice points into.  New combat skills (round kick, tiger claw, eagle strike etc.) should be trained only a few points and allowed to go up naturally with use. Granted, it can get kind of harrowing waiting for level 17, but it's well worth it.  Remember though, just because you click feign death and fall to the ground does not mean it succeeded - you'll find that out when you click the button and the monster keeps attacking you.  Make sure you leave yourself enough HP to absorb a few more blows while you're on the ground - feign death recycles very 10 seconds or so, and can be clicked while you're on the ground!  Feign death also has some shady uses that won't win you any points with zone inhabitants, but work well for disposing of that kill stealing wizard ;)<BR>
<BR>
3) Quick attacks.  No other melee class can dish out as much damage as quickly as a monk, aside from perhaps a rogue (both monks and rogues get dual wield and double attack fairly quickly, though monks have a slight edge with dual wield).  By the time you hit level 20, your dual wield will be over 130, and your double attack in the area of 100.  How many times you hit your enemy has alot to do with their agility... a brownie, for example, won't be hit all that many times while a mummy will be dogmeat.  For this reason it is important to pick your fights carefully... all blue cons are DEFINATELY not created equal.<BR>
<BR>
4) Mend.  For a melee class, monks heal awfully quickly.  Try being a warrior for a day and you'll see what I mean.  Granted, monks have lots of hit points which can slow things down, but an automatic healing of one third your hit points every six minutes cannot be beat.  Some folks will tell you to pour lots of practice points into mend, but it's a much better idea to put in only a few in the beginning and practice it religiously.  Even if you don't need the health, click it any time you can - until it reaches level 70 or so it won't work reliably anyway, and may actually worsen your wounds (nothing like dropping one third of your hit poits during a tough fight!).  At level 90 it will hardly ever fail, and will be there when you need it.<BR>
<BR>
5) Headband and sash quests.  Unique to the monk class and very very useful; these items will provide some great stat bonuses at earlier levels than most other classes get.  As of today, the furthest you can get is the fifth level (purple) headband, which I recently achieved.  Wow!  These things are great!  The purple headband provides over ten points of stat increases, an item that on the mass market would cost hundreds and hundreds of platinum.  Take advantage of these quests!  The later ones will cost you a bit of cash if you decided to buy the items rather than aquire them, but they are well worth it.  NOTE: if you start in Qeynos, you will have to raise your faction with the Freeport monk guild before they will allow you to do their quests, but if you start in Freeport you can do the Qeynos quests as-is.<BR>
<BR>
I hope this sheds some new light on the monk class.  Above all, my advice is to TRAVEL!  Don't stay in Blackburrow all the time, go out and see the world!  You don't have to be constantly on the move, but try and find a zone that has the best ratio of blue cons.  Standing around a newbie zone waiting for the one mob your level to spawn is not only tiresome but makes leveling very slow going.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
